JimBalcomb — Yesterday at 7:33 PM
@harrand In your experience, when writing tests, would you use the game/engine functions to set up the game-state/data for the tests or would you make new code to manually recreate what's needed?
e.g., if I wanted to test something like Kill_Unit(), does it make sense to run whatever is 'Init Game' and then Create_Unit() for the unit I want to kill?
This all seems so weirdly more complicated for a game, but it seems like that perspective should workd until you get to 'new game'/'load saved game'.


WGG — 12:09 AM
most of the time (or maybe even all the time) you want the test to be as narrow as possible and only test one specific thing.
in your case the approach should be creating the most basic valid "unit" object, then calling the kill_unit function, and finally observing the changes and comparing to expectations
if you have e.g. an ecs in place and creating a unit has dependencies for that, that's when you create mocks


