harrand — 4:36 AM
depending on how you have architected your tests this ranges from horrible to nightmarish

for in-game functionality unit tests I have my tests as functions that assume the game is already running, so you can run them all on a single running invocation of the game

if each unit test involves setting up the game from scratch not only will they become very slow your unit tests instead morph into integration tests

if you have save/load states then it becomes even better



dascandy — 4:38 AM
one great setup is to create a "game state" that does all the game logic, and a "renderer" that reads from the game state to draw whatever is going on in your view. You can then write tests that use only the game state without any renderer to do game logic checks



harrand — 4:39 AM
even just a headless mode would suffice for that if you have a lil build farm to work with
if I have time for tests I'll most likely spend it writing integration tests for mechanics that i think are most likely to regress between changes



dascandy — 4:41 AM
same, first write the tests for things that are easy to test and hard to debug/fix if they break


